{"cursor":"3714","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nA 'production' or 'production rule' in computer science is a [[rewrite rule]]\nspecifying a symbol substitution that can be recursively performed to generate\nnew symbol sequences. A finite set of productions P is the main\ncomponent in the specification of a formal grammar (specifically a generative\ngrammar). The other components are a finite set N of nonterminal\nsymbols, a finite set (known as an alphabet) \\Sigma of terminal\nsymbols that is disjoint from N and a distinguished symbol S\n\\in N that is the start symbol.\n\nIn an unrestricted grammar, a production is of the form u \\to v\nwhere u and v are arbitrary strings of terminals and\nnonterminals however u may not be the empty string. If\nv is the empty string, this is denoted by the symbol\n\\epsilon , or \\lambda (rather than leave the right-hand\nside blank). So productions are of the form:\n\n: (N \\cup \\Sigma)^*N(N \\cup \\Sigma)^* \\to (N \\cup \\Sigma)^*\n\nWhere {}^{+} is the Kleene plus operator, {}^{*} is\nthe Kleene star operator, and \\cup denotes set union.\n\nThe other types of formal grammar in the Chomsky hierarchy impose additional\nrestrictions on what constitutes a production. Notably in a context-free\ngrammar, the left-hand side of a production must be a single nonterminal symbol.\nSo productions are of the form:\n\n: N \\to (N \\cup \\Sigma)^*\n","linknr":138,"url":"Production_(computer_science)","recorded":1362372552,"links":14,"instances":["set_theory"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Grammar","Natural language processing"],"headings":["Grammar generation","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/4/c/44c29edb103a2872f519ad0c9a0fdaaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/6/4/a643a0ef5974b64678111d03125054fc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/ma